My first Met Gala was in 2015: I was invited by @calvinklein and I was so scared to be there. 
2015 was a very depressing time of my life: I was living in Los Angeles, was in a relationship that wasn‚Äôt working, I felt so alone and professionally in cage, while other people were making most of my decisions. 
Met Gala was still amazing, but if I think of that year I can only think ‚ÄúGood job Chiara for getting out of that time of your life, creating your own rules and becoming your boss, making your OWN decisions and creating the family you‚Äôve always dreamt of‚Äù 
If 2015 Chiara could see 2022 Chiara I think she would cry with happiness, and this is what this Met Gala means to me: hand in hand with my husband, happy and proud.

For the most part of my teenage/adult life my biggest physical insecurity has been my skin: I‚Äôve always had breakouts/acne and showing my skin when it was inflammed was very triggering for me. 
In the past 6 years my skin has changed and got so much better: what really helped me was balancing my hormones with inositol (totally natural), live a happier life and not think about it too much. Every once in a while I get breakouts, and It‚Äôs totally ok and I made peace with the situation. 
The day we were finally discharged from the hospital I had a very bad rash on the right part of my chin: I blame it on my hormones + obviously super high stress level. I could have avoided talking about it and showing it but then I was thinking.. Why should I not talk about it? We have to normalize bad skin days too, and not having the pressure to ever feel perfect üôèüèª

Last Saturday It was Leone‚Äôs 4th birthday. We had organized a big party with all of his classmates and friends since he hadn‚Äôt really celebrated the past two years due to the pandemic, but we had to change it the day before: daddy had to go through surgery on Tuesday and It was important not to get covid before that (so not so many people involved).
So we only had his five best friends come, and family. 
Our mood wasn‚Äôt the most festive but It ended up being a great party for our little one üíñ Grateful for these memories üôèüèª

This was pretty much our week after Fede‚Äôs diagnosis and leading up to his surgery: we took some time off social media, spent as much time as possible with the kids, went for a lot of visits and exams, went for walks, had gelato sitting on a bench, spent some time with his closest friends, recorded some music (he did and I listened), slept with Leo in our bed (he usually sleeps in his room) and celebrated his 4th birthday. 
Most of this time felt like a blur: it was like time had stopped and I was scared like never before in my life that something bad could have happened. 
Thanks life for turning things around for the best üôèüèªü§ûüèªüôèüèª

This pic was taken on Monday afternoon at the hospital, the day before his pancreas delicate surgery. 
We were scared for everything: his diagnosis, his surgery, his recovery, our life and the fiture of our family. 
The surgery on Tuesday went well, and he‚Äôs now recovering and hopefully this will only be a bad memory that taught us, once again, the importance of enjoying life to the fullest, everyday üôèüèª 
Thanks to all the people who made us feel their love, reached out and said a prayer for us, it gave us a lot of strenght üôèüèª

My speech last night receiving GQ Woman of the Year Award üôèüèª
‚ÄúI am so proud to receive this award today after a very challenging year and a half we all have experienced. 
What everyone, me included, has tried to do this year was to help the community, and I am not talking about social media community only, but also the real community out there in the world. 
One year and half today my husband and I raised 5 milion euros and we built a new intensive care unit of a hospital in Milan, my hometown, for the Covid emergency and we did it in just 2 weeks, which is pretty incredible. 
We also tried to connect fabric producers and all the clothing companies to make face masks for the hospitals of our country. 
For the first time, in a globalised world, we started to think local. 
Wa wanted to support people all all over the world using our voices and media influence by helping them to connect and concretely help each other.
This is the reason why today I am so proud to receive this award. 
Because I know that I am more than just a pretty face giving fashion advices and I hope I demonstrated that change can come from anyone. Everyone can make the difference. Everyone, little by little and fighting every day, can create a positive change. 
For this reason I want to dedicate this award to all the women, and human beings, that are brave enough to believe in the power of people.
Thank you everyone üôèüèª‚Äù

Since so many are asking about it here is Leo‚Äôs birth story ‚ù§Ô∏è We spent most of the pregnancy between Milan and Los Angeles and moved permanently to LA around my 29th week to be able to deliver Leo there. Until the 32nd week it was the easiest pregnancy ever: I was able to travel, work and do basically everything I used to do before. From week 32 I started having problems with my placenta. My liquids were also low and I was put at home rest with the idea to deliver max at 36 or 37 weeks. At 37 weeks my doc said it was safer not to wait any longer: at 1 am on March 19th I started induction at the hospital with a foley balloon and crazy (and super painful)  contractions. After I was a bit dialeted they took off the balloon and started oxytocin to prepare my body to deliver. A few hours later (at around 11 am) they broke my water (it‚Äôs like that during induction) and I requested my epidural (loved it). Everything was going smooth until Leo‚Äôs heartbeat started racing in the afternoon so the they had to give me oxygen, slow down the oxytocin and I started being very scared. At around 7 pm they told me I had an infection going on and gave me antibiotics. At this time I was super scared and thought they would opt for a C section (after 18 hours of labor) but then my doc came and I was dialeted enough to push and have a natural birth üòç I pushed with Fede by my side and at 11.37 pm (22 hours after I started induction) I finally met my Leo. Best moment of my life so far. I could hold him for 30 seconds then they had to check on him for a few minutes before giving him back to me, and in that moment I couldn‚Äôt stop crying from happiness (see photos). Giving birth really is a lifetime experience üôèüèª
